10862 /*----------------------------------------------------------- */
10863 /* Some useful macros for allocating data memory */
10864 /*----------------------------------------------------------- */
10865 
10866 /* The following macros require an argument N that specifies */
10867 /* alignment. N must a power of two, minimum value = 2. */
10868 /* For example, to declare an uninitialized array in X memory */
10869 /* that is aligned to a 32 byte address: */
10870 /* */
10871 /* int _XBSS(32) xbuf[16]; */
10872 /* */
10873 #define _XBSS(N) __attribute__((space(xmemory),far,aligned(N)))
10874 #define _XDATA(N) __attribute__((space(xmemory),far,aligned(N)))
10875 #define _YBSS(N) __attribute__((space(ymemory),far,aligned(N)))
10876 #define _YDATA(N) __attribute__((space(ymemory),far,aligned(N)))
10877 
10878 /* The following macros do not require an argument. They can */
10879 /* be used to locate a variable in persistent data memory or */
10880 /* in near data memory. For example, to declare two variables */
10881 /* that retain their values across a device reset: */
10882 /* */
10883 /* int _PERSISTENT var1,var2; */
10884 /* */
10885 #define _PERSISTENT __attribute__((persistent))
10886 #define _NEAR __attribute__((near))
10887 
10888 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
10889 /* Some useful macros for declaring functions */
10890 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
10891 
10892 /* The following macros can be used to declare interrupt */
10893 /* service routines (ISRs). For example, to declare an ISR */
10894 /* for the timer1 interrupt: */
10895 /* */
10896 /* void _ISR _T1Interrupt(void); */
10897 /* */
10898 /* To declare an ISR for the SPI1 interrupt with fast */
10899 /* context save: */
10900 /* */
10901 /* void _ISRFAST _SPI1Interrupt(void); */
10902 /* */
10903 /* Note: ISRs will be installed into the interrupt vector */
10904 /* tables automatically if the reserved names listed in the */
10905 /* MPLAB C30 Compiler User's Guide (DS51284) are used. */
10906 /* */
10907 #define _ISR __attribute__((interrupt))
10908 #define _ISRFAST __attribute__((interrupt, shadow))
10909 
10910 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
10911 /* Some useful macros for changing the CPU IPL */
10912 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
10913 
10914 /* The following macros can be used to modify the current CPU */
10915 /* IPL. The definition of the macro may vary from device to */
10916 /* device. */
10917 /* */
10918 /* To safely set the CPU IPL, use SET_CPU_IPL(ipl); the */
10919 /* valid range of ipl is 0-7, it may be any expression. */
10920 /* */
10921 /* SET_CPU_IPL(7); */
10922 /* */
10923 /* To preserve the current IPL and save it use */
10924 /* SET_AND_SAVE_CPU_IPL(save_to, ipl); the valid range of ipl */
10925 /* is 0-7 and may be any expression, save_to should denote */
10926 /* some temporary storage. */
10927 /* */
10928 /* int old_ipl; */
10929 /* */
10930 /* SET_AND_SAVE_CPU_IPL(old_ipl, 7); */
10931 /* */
10932 /* The IPL can be restored with RESTORE_CPU_IPL(saved_to) */
10933 /* */
10934 /* RESTORE_CPU_IPL(old_ipl); */
10935 
10936 #define SET_CPU_IPL(ipl) { \
10937  int DISI_save; \
10938  \
10939  DISI_save = DISICNT; \
10940  asm volatile ("disi #0x3FFF"); \
10941  SRbits.IPL = ipl; \
10942  DISICNT = DISI_save; } (void) 0;
10943 
10944 #define SET_AND_SAVE_CPU_IPL(save_to, ipl) { \
10945  save_to = SRbits.IPL; \
10946  SET_CPU_IPL(ipl); } (void) 0;
10947 
10948 #define RESTORE_CPU_IPL(saved_to) SET_CPU_IPL(saved_to)
10949
